    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Napster: Unplugged?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eric Vadon letter on Matt Richtel's July 9 holds downloading digital MP3 files via Napster does not dimimish original copy and makes original more valuable</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your example of taking someone's shoes as a comparison to sharing music via Napster is inadequate, because shoes are a resource that only one person at a time can use. On the other hand, if I were in possession of some pair of ''magical'' shoes and were able to create a perfect copy for another person to use, might I not be seen as unfair to deny others the use of my shoes?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your example of taking someone's shoes as a comparison to sharing music via Napster is inadequate, because shoes are a resource that only one person at a time can use. On the other hand, if I were in possession of some pair of ''magical'' shoes and were able to create a perfect copy for another person to use, might I not be seen as unfair to deny others the use of my shoes?</p>
        <p>The Internet's magic is that it is a resource that is not used up. Downloading a digital MP3 file via Napster in no way diminishes the original copy, and one could argue that it makes the original more valuable, because the more people listen to a band, the more popular it becomes.</p>
        <p>ERIC VADON  San Francisco, July 9</p>
      </block>
